We've had this debate before (albeit I was a bit buzzed if I remember correctly), but because I like you I'm gonna try again. First we are discovering more "Biblical" texts - with our progressing knowledge and changing world we are able to get deeper into the text

Remember that the Bible is DIVINELY INSPIRED - it is a perfect text and it was WRITTEN with the knowledge that it is going to be read by us TODAY. Ergo it is written to be interpreted in new ways by us, using our new knowledge of the sciences and changing state of our world

For example the futurist interpretation of the Final days, the abortion clinic interpretation of Moloch, modern corporations as Mammon... all of this is there. We do not need new books for the Bible, we need to go deeper in what we already have: what you wish for is no different

Than going to the depths of space before we have explored our oceans! Everything that we need has already been given to us and it is up to us to fully use the tools that we have, to truly interpret the Bible (we have just started with the first layers! we have so much much more!)

It is one belief that in Heaven we are going to be eternally moving closer and closer to God, revealing more and more knowledge about him - Heaven might be a state of progress! Imagine how much more there is in the Bible that we are blind to see. Now, for why I think Thomas's

Gospel might be satanically inspired, just like a part of the Qu'ran. First it refers to "secret sayings" - in Christianity we do not have secret sayings. All is said clear and loud, but the interpretation of it is the hard part

That's why they hated Christ - he said all out loud, but it was hard for them to understand it. The thinking that Christ said some things in private to him - that he withdrew with Thomas and reveal the "gnosis' to him is blasphemous

There is a difference between a parable and gnosis: Christ spoke unto all who wanted to hear him. Some were deaf to his words - that's the point of the parable. But no one was left without hearing it.

We are, but we should not take other books as Gospels other than the 4 Gospels we have - the number of them carries symbolism too, 5 Gospels would be absurd, number makes no sense: and absurd things come from the devils

Of course not! But everytrhing that we NEED is given to us there. You may use fine and special dining instruments for oysters, paste etc. But why have different utensils when a fork and a spoon might do the same work without confusing you?

all right, you have studied symbolism etc before, why would the Bible have more than four Gospels? 4 are the corners of the world, 4 is the number of the world, 4 Gospels are the number to encompass Christ

Yet he speaks to others (albeit in parables) - in Thomas's gospel the knowledge is given to but a single individual. The entire thing about going away from the others to share "secret knowledge" with the "enlightened" student: it smells of gnosticism from afar

And as I said it is irrelevant to us if other stories of Christ's life exist - I know a lot of them that I have researched irl for, from folklore mythology etc and I like them - does not mean I believe them to be truth

As I stated, we have been given all the tools we need and there's no point in deluding ourselves that we need anything more. And I ask again: why 5 instead of 4 Gospels? Why everything else is symbolic but the number of Gospels shall be meaningless?
